But there are some hidden
complexities inherent

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:13.670
in mounting a large AV
collection that need to be sorted

00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:15.300
out before we just put it online.

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:20.200
And so, I'll just walk you
through a few of those things.

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:22.020
OK, so first some context, right?

00:08:22.020 --> 00:08:27.980
The date span of materials in our
archives ranges from 1890 to 2016.

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:31.090
So, that's about 125 years
worth of documentation

00:08:31.090 --> 00:08:33.270
on every imaginable
audiovisual format.

00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:38.930
So, we're a fairly contemporary
archive by many standards.

00:08:38.930 --> 00:08:42.340
And so, the topic today
is the orange there.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:47.840
It's the disc era which was
largely the '30s and '40s.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:53.510 position:56%
And so, I also mentioned descriptive
tools that help you access these,

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:54.810
and that's the card catalog.

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:56.830
And that was started in 1933.

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:58.380
I'll talk about that more later.

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:01.260
Because the Lomaxes were eager
to start publishing the material,

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:04.020
they collected right away and
they needed a way to organize it.

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:08.360
And so flash forward to 2007,

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:12.030
that card catalog information
went online.

00:09:14.250 --> 00:09:17.870
So now flash forward to
2016, where we are today,

00:09:17.870 --> 00:09:21.240 position:56%
and we are a dozen years away from
marking the hundred year anniversary

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:25.210
of the archive founded in 1928.

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:30.610
The date for us, 2028, has come
to not only mark the anniversary

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:34.610
of the archive, but it sort of sits
out in the distance as a marker

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:37.940
for where we want to be
with our preservation work

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:40.420
on audiovisual materials.

00:09:40.420 --> 00:09:47.410 position:56%
So, the Library of Congress National
Recording Preservation Plan says

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:52.360
that many analog recordings must
be digitized within the next 15

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:56.660
to 20 years, and this is to avoid
degradation and obsolescence.

00:09:56.660 --> 00:10:00.600
And so, we figured that by the
time we hit the hundred year mark,

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:03.290
we ought to have this problem
solved or at least well

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:07.570
in hand as much as we can.

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:12.150
So, this is why we are preparing
to conduct comprehensive assessment

00:10:12.150 --> 00:10:17.860
of our AV holdings and start making
some moves toward seeking external

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:23.820
funding for ramping up that work.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:27.050
OK. So in the digital world--
Well, in analog world, of course,

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:30.840
you've got two main pieces of
information from the field.

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:34.350
You've got the recording itself and
then you've got the field notes.

00:10:34.350 --> 00:10:37.320
Now, often, they would use disc
sleeves to write information

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:40.430
about the recording and they
would sometimes use notebooks.

00:10:40.430 --> 00:10:43.120
And I'm ignoring the fact that
they took photographs just

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:44.420
for simplicity's sake.

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:46.500
But yes, those are
the main components

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:49.530
of the fieldwork from this era.

00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:53.340
So in the digital world, that turns
into audio files and metadata,

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:57.190
right, metadata, description
about data.

00:10:57.190 --> 00:11:10.090
OK. So, WPA workers created the
catalog in the '30s and '40s,

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:14.750 position:56%
and the archive staff then continued
to build it through the late 1960s.

00:11:14.750 --> 00:11:16.050
It's still in our reading room.

00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:19.190
It's kind of a cool artifact,
but it also does get active use.

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:23.440
People like to go to it even
though it is also online.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:26.450
And here are the happy
people who made it go online.

00:11:26.450 --> 00:11:28.460
Some of them are in
the room, I believe.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:31.330
This was a real game
changer for the archives

00:11:31.330 --> 00:11:34.170
and it remains a widely
used resource.

00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:38.200
Not only was the information
transcribed into a database,

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:42.250
but the cards themselves were
imaged and included online.

