00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:42.520 position:56%
and thank you to the American
Folklife Center for this opportunity

00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:44.140
for the grant to do this work.

00:28:44.140 --> 00:28:45.630
It was such a gift.

00:28:45.630 --> 00:28:48.460
I did a project called
American Hair,

00:28:48.460 --> 00:28:51.360
the document of beauty shop culture
throughout the United States.

00:28:51.360 --> 00:28:56.190
And I traveled over 20,000 miles
conducting interviews in salons

00:28:56.190 --> 00:29:01.140
that served everyone from
African-American to Appalachian,

00:29:01.140 --> 00:29:07.170
Cajun, Dominican, Gullah,
Japanese, Lumbee Indian, Pakistani.

00:29:07.170 --> 00:29:10.520
I also interviewed some of
the industry powerhouses

00:29:10.520 --> 00:29:15.530
like the Vidal Sassoon
family, Tabatha Coffey from

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:20.210
"Tabatha Takes Over",
Bob Marley's hairdresser,

00:29:21.290 --> 00:29:23.420
Paul Mitchell and the like.

00:29:23.420 --> 00:29:24.720
So let me see.

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:26.180
I'm going to advance.

00:29:26.180 --> 00:29:30.740
OK. And I started this project
in 2006 because I was sitting

00:29:30.740 --> 00:29:34.500
in my hair salon for about
10 years and realized

00:29:34.500 --> 00:29:37.460
that in the whole time I'd been
there, I've never seen anybody

00:29:37.460 --> 00:29:39.470
but black people in there.

00:29:39.470 --> 00:29:44.250
And one day a white woman walked
in and wanted to get her hair done.

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:46.940
She just wanted to wash
and set, really simple.

00:29:46.940 --> 00:29:49.640
And my hairdresser shooed her away.

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:53.540 position:56%
Well, she was nice but she was
like, you know, no, I don't do that.

00:29:53.540 --> 00:29:56.200
And then, when she
left, the woman left,

00:29:56.200 --> 00:29:58.930
my hairdresser said,
I don't do white hair.

00:29:58.930 --> 00:30:00.340
And I was shocked.

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:01.640
I was like, "Oh my god."

00:30:01.640 --> 00:30:05.380
You know, I thought maybe this
is Gigi's exterior of the salon,

00:30:05.380 --> 00:30:07.050
and I felt uncomfortable.

00:30:07.050 --> 00:30:10.530
I was like, am I part of a secret
society that I don't know about?

00:30:10.530 --> 00:30:14.910
Because I lived in San Francisco,
one of the most diverse places

00:30:14.910 --> 00:30:20.440
in the world, and I just be-- it
was glaring how segregated it was.

00:30:20.440 --> 00:30:23.280
And that's when I started
this project.

00:30:23.280 --> 00:30:26.830
For the next several years, I just
would sit under the hair dryer

00:30:26.830 --> 00:30:30.690
and just study what was
happening in the salon.

00:30:30.690 --> 00:30:33.830
And I realized, you know,
I watched Gigi, our--

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:36.840
my hairdresser, counsel
us, support us.

00:30:36.840 --> 00:30:41.080
I mean she-- Everybody went through
every kind of emotion imaginable

00:30:41.080 --> 00:30:44.490
in that salon and Gigi
was there for us.

00:30:44.490 --> 00:30:47.620
And I realized that she was
protecting this environment

00:30:47.620 --> 00:30:50.040
that was rooted in
culture and ritual.

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:54.260
And I wondered, you know, if other
salons are like this, you know,

00:30:54.260 --> 00:30:59.280
what about Japanese
salons or Pakistani salons.

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:01.400
And so, that's when
I got the opportunity

00:31:01.400 --> 00:31:03.520
to do this project
when I got this grant.

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:08.840
And it was interesting because then
I had to go outside of my little,

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:12.990
you know, womb basically,
that was so protected,

00:31:12.990 --> 00:31:15.730
into these other salons
are very intimate spaces.

00:31:15.730 --> 00:31:21.310
And so, when I tried to go to see
a Chinese salon in San Francisco,

00:31:21.310 --> 00:31:24.120
it was like, you know,
walking in and the music stops

00:31:24.120 --> 00:31:27.220
and everybody looks at you,
like what are you doing here.

00:31:27.220 --> 00:31:29.890
And I tell them I'm not
here to get my hair done

00:31:29.890 --> 00:31:32.090
and they would just
be really relieved.

00:31:32.090 --> 00:31:34.710
And that look of relief
would be like, oh god,

00:31:34.710 --> 00:31:36.620
you know, then why are you here?

00:31:36.620 --> 00:31:39.680
And when I would explain the
project, you know, I would just--

00:31:39.680 --> 00:31:44.590
generally people were not, that
one out of eight, that's liberal,

00:31:44.590 --> 00:31:47.240
would allow me to even
to do the project.

00:31:47.240 --> 00:31:49.320
It was very hard to get access.

00:31:49.320 --> 00:31:54.070
Having an outsider come in, I
mean, I'm there in their face

00:31:54.070 --> 00:31:57.930
with this camera was, you
know, it was kind of invasive.

00:31:57.930 --> 00:32:01.920
And ironically, after getting
the Library of Congress grant,

00:32:01.920 --> 00:32:05.010
I thought, "Oh, this will
make it more important."

00:32:05.010 --> 00:32:09.270
And I mean actually made it more
difficult because a lot the--

00:32:09.270 --> 00:32:12.880
these were, you know,
immigrant-based communities,

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:16.880
these were small, you know,
they just heard government.

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:18.610
They were like, "Definitely not."

00:32:18.610 --> 00:32:21.070
You know, we don't want to
have anything to do with that.

00:32:21.070 --> 00:32:24.350
So, it was challenging.

00:32:24.350 --> 00:32:25.910
But I continued on.

00:32:25.910 --> 00:32:31.070
I continued to study the anatomy
of hair and understand that most

00:32:31.070 --> 00:32:34.090
of the salons were segregated
because of hair texture.

00:32:34.090 --> 00:32:37.240
You know, it wasn't just culture
but there was a logistical issue

00:32:37.240 --> 00:32:41.520 position:56%
of hairdressers not knowing how to
deal with that kind of hair texture.

00:32:41.520 --> 00:32:44.940
And so, I learned about those
differences, the difference

00:32:44.940 --> 00:32:48.770
between Asian hair and
why it's so hard to curl.

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:53.300
How it's, you know-- why
black hair just tends to be

00:32:53.300 --> 00:32:55.320
so much kinkier and curlier.

00:32:55.320 --> 00:33:02.770
I went to a Japanese salon and
saw-- it's actually in DC here.

00:33:02.770 --> 00:33:05.210
And you can see how, you
know, this contraption,

00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:08.220 position:56%
there's all these chemicals, there's
all these things that they use

00:33:08.220 --> 00:33:13.550
that the salon owner would have to
go to Japan to get these materials.

00:33:13.550 --> 00:33:15.330
So, you know, it's not just--

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:18.840
I mean there's a comfort factor why
people group themselves, you know,

00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:20.140
amongst people like them.

00:33:20.140 --> 00:33:21.730
But then, there's this
logistical issue.

00:33:21.730 --> 00:33:24.320
So, I learned about that.

00:33:24.320 --> 00:33:27.810
And that, you know, easy
breezy kind of wave pattern,

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:33.920
that took about five hours for
her to get that, that look.

00:33:35.030 --> 00:33:41.070
I also went to Bollywood Salon
which was Pakistani in Queens.

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:43.490
Shahzad here doing hair.

00:33:43.490 --> 00:33:45.400
He said, you know, the most--

00:33:45.400 --> 00:33:51.130
He probably did Jennifer Aniston's
haircut for 30 years of his career.

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:54.230
And it's very difficult
to get Indian hair

00:33:54.230 --> 00:33:56.970
to fall like Jennifer Aniston.

00:33:56.970 --> 00:33:59.540
So, he talked about that.

00:33:59.540 --> 00:34:02.300
I looked at, you know, there's
this assumption that, oh,

00:34:02.300 --> 00:34:07.830
the blond straight hair,
they have it easy and realize

00:34:07.830 --> 00:34:11.860
that it's very time consuming
and expensive to be blond.

00:34:11.860 --> 00:34:15.500
And that has its own
hurdles to deal with.

00:34:15.500 --> 00:34:18.130
I was also very interested

00:34:18.130 --> 00:34:22.820
in the labor involved
in doing hairdressing.

00:34:22.820 --> 00:34:25.820
You know, I interviewed
Farrah Fawcett's hairdresser

00:34:25.820 --> 00:34:30.180
and he said there's
75 steps to a haircut.

00:34:30.180 --> 00:34:32.260
And so, he went through
that, just the architecture

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:37.030
of building a haircut and how much,
you know, knowledge goes into that.

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:41.560
I went to a traditional
African salon

00:34:41.560 --> 00:34:44.510
and it was a home salon
in Philadelphia.

00:34:44.510 --> 00:34:47.350
And that was one of the most
interesting interviews I did

00:34:47.350 --> 00:34:50.650
because their hair-- it
wasn't just about the hair.

00:34:50.650 --> 00:34:54.150
It was really, really tied to
their culture and identity.

00:34:54.150 --> 00:34:57.210
And what they end up
doing a lot is trying

00:34:57.210 --> 00:35:00.170
to fix black hair that's
been damaged

00:35:00.170 --> 00:35:02.170
because of the straightening
and all the chemicals.

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:06.090
So here, Ifama is getting
braids, which is her natural hair

00:35:06.090 --> 00:35:08.670
but at the top it's all extensions.

00:35:08.670 --> 00:35:11.250
It's all fake hair until
her natural hair grows

00:35:11.250 --> 00:35:16.090
out because she damaged it
so badly from chemicals.

00:35:16.090 --> 00:35:21.560
And they were trained in these
traditional African hairstyles

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:24.150
so they had incredible knowledge.

00:35:24.150 --> 00:35:27.190
And there's also I found
a white hairdresser

00:35:27.190 --> 00:35:30.400
who has primarily black clientele.

00:35:30.400 --> 00:35:31.700
Her name is Rina.

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:33.000
She's Sicilian.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:37.430
So again in Sicily they tend to
have that kinkier texture hair

00:35:37.430 --> 00:35:40.910
so she kind of wasn't afraid of
it and knew how to handle that.

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:44.720
So, she was amazing.

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:52.630
And you can see her
straightening, the transformation.

00:35:52.630 --> 00:35:56.050
And I was also interested in
multicultural salons because,

00:35:56.050 --> 00:36:00.520
you know, with the fact that,
you know, we're living in a world

00:36:00.520 --> 00:36:04.140
where people are not of one
race, a lot of people choose

00:36:04.140 --> 00:36:09.020
to say I'm not identified
with a particular race and one

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:12.480
in seven marriages or interracial.

00:36:12.480 --> 00:36:15.190
So, we're looking at there's
different hair textures that are,

00:36:15.190 --> 00:36:19.010
you know, just popping up
and people are demanding

00:36:19.010 --> 00:36:21.230
to be served in regular salons.

00:36:21.230 --> 00:36:24.700
They don't necessarily
want to go to a black salon

00:36:24.700 --> 00:36:27.500
or a Chinese or Japanese salon.

00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:30.970
So, there are multicultural
salons popping

00:36:30.970 --> 00:36:34.360
up where the hairdressers are
trained to work on different types

00:36:34.360 --> 00:36:38.430
of hair and people who are adopting
kids of a different race can go

00:36:38.430 --> 00:36:41.330
into the same salon and get
their hair done as their child.

00:36:41.330 --> 00:36:44.010
So, this is a big demand right now.

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:49.610
And Ms. Mia here is half Brazilian
and half black and, you know,

00:36:49.610 --> 00:36:52.560
so her Brazilian mother who has
a straight hair is like, oh,

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:55.740
it's such a relief that I
can finally go to a salon

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:58.990
where we can both be served.

00:36:58.990 --> 00:37:01.840
I was also looking at
Lumbee Indian women

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:06.130
and there's an African
bloodline in the Lumbeean tribe,

00:37:06.130 --> 00:37:08.210
and so kinky hair does come up.

00:37:08.210 --> 00:37:12.180
But this was a daughter of
a mother who had curly hair

00:37:12.180 --> 00:37:13.970
and was really ashamed to have--

00:37:13.970 --> 00:37:15.860
because all her brothers and
sisters had straight hair

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:17.610
that were traditional Indian

00:37:17.610 --> 00:37:20.620
but she always hid her curls
and was really ashamed.

00:37:20.620 --> 00:37:24.610
And now her daughter has this
curly hair and embracing her curls.

00:37:24.610 --> 00:37:31.100 position:56%
And so looking at the transformation
of time was also really was special

00:37:31.100 --> 00:37:36.140
to see people changing
their identity around that.

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:39.600
And also, you know,
if you are-- have--

00:37:39.600 --> 00:37:41.780
of Asian descent and
you want dreadlocks,

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:45.640
that's a whole process that,
you know, they have created

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:47.450
at Twisted Salon in New Orleans

00:37:47.450 --> 00:37:51.780
where she had a steamer
nozzle attached to a hose and,

00:37:51.780 --> 00:37:53.080
you know, and back combed.

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:56.880
And it was really complicated but
they could dread somebody's hair.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:59.610
So, that was another shoe.

00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:04.730
And I went to Orthodox
Jewish salon in Brooklyn

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:08.540
and thought I'd be walking into
some place that was so, you know,

00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:15.560
I want to say repressed but
just, you know, very somber.

00:38:15.560 --> 00:38:20.510
But they have one of the
leading, you know, salons of--

00:38:20.510 --> 00:38:23.380
for wigs for people
of African descent.

00:38:23.380 --> 00:38:28.460 position:56%
People from all over the country buy
their wigs and they've really broken

00:38:28.460 --> 00:38:29.840
