00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:23.550
Before we get there,
I'm going to talk

00:49:23.550 --> 00:49:24.850
about what is a domestic worker.

00:49:24.850 --> 00:49:27.250
Someone who works in another
person's home and cares

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:31.360
for their children or an
elderly person, is a housekeeper,

00:49:31.360 --> 00:49:35.540
does other work in or around the
home like gardening or repair work.

00:49:35.540 --> 00:49:38.790
Domestic Workers United is a
membership based organization.

00:49:38.790 --> 00:49:40.090
They're not a union.

00:49:40.090 --> 00:49:44.040
They are base of Caribbean, Latina
and African nannies, housekeepers

00:49:44.040 --> 00:49:48.460
and elderly caregivers in New
York, organizing for power, respect

00:49:48.460 --> 00:49:53.160
and fair labor standards to end
exploitation and oppression.

00:49:53.160 --> 00:49:59.420
So the two key terms here are
trying to fight for recognition

00:49:59.420 --> 00:50:02.180
that this work is real work.

00:50:02.180 --> 00:50:05.180
As of today, DWU, that's
how I'm going to refer

00:50:05.180 --> 00:50:06.570
to Domestic Workers United,

00:50:06.570 --> 00:50:09.230
has organized over
6000 domestic workers.

00:50:09.230 --> 00:50:14.130
There's an estimated 300,000
domestic workers in New York State.

00:50:14.130 --> 00:50:18.770
So the goals as I mentioned,
Domestic Workers United wants

00:50:18.770 --> 00:50:21.640
to make sure there is equal
rights for domestic workers,

00:50:21.640 --> 00:50:24.040
but the recognition of the
occupation of as real work.

00:50:24.040 --> 00:50:28.320
One of the common phrases
you hear them talk about is

00:50:28.320 --> 00:50:32.520
that they do the work that
makes all other work possible.

00:50:32.520 --> 00:50:36.250
They work for very wealthy
lawyers, doctors, you name it,

00:50:36.250 --> 00:50:39.370
in New York City, Long
Island as well.

00:50:39.370 --> 00:50:43.380
And in 2010-- So Domestic
Workers United started in 2000.

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:47.270
In 2010, they passed something
called the Domestic Workers Bill

00:50:47.270 --> 00:50:48.570
of Rights.

00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:53.010
So this bill of rights was
to guide domestic workers

00:50:53.010 --> 00:50:56.740
and have them communicate
their rights

00:50:56.740 --> 00:50:58.730
to avoid harassment on the job.

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:02.860
Sexual harassment or harassment
based on gender or ethnicity

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:06.080
to advocate and to understand
that they get days off.

00:51:06.080 --> 00:51:09.840
That once they work
over-- And also, yeah,

00:51:09.840 --> 00:51:11.960
once they work a certain amount
of time, they're required

00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:14.430
to have one day off a week
at least if they're in--

00:51:14.430 --> 00:51:17.030
they're working in-house
or a live-in.

00:51:17.030 --> 00:51:22.030
They are required to have 24 full
hours off of that seven days.

00:51:22.030 --> 00:51:24.500
It taught domestic workers
to use their rights,

00:51:24.500 --> 00:51:29.070
how to advocate the fact that
they have rights and reinforce

00:51:29.070 --> 00:51:31.580
that the rights applied to
domestic workers regardless

00:51:31.580 --> 00:51:32.880
of immigration status.

00:51:32.880 --> 00:51:36.020
And this is the key
thing for all the workers

00:51:36.020 --> 00:51:39.230
that Domestic Workers United worked
with because they don't have--

00:51:39.230 --> 00:51:42.890
Many of them, I'd say I think 75%

00:51:42.890 --> 00:51:45.170
of the ones we interviewed
do not have--

00:51:45.170 --> 00:51:49.410
their immigration statuses
is cloudy and difficult

00:51:49.410 --> 00:51:53.130
that they don't have the ability
to advocate for themselves.

00:51:53.130 --> 00:51:54.430
They're afraid.

00:51:54.430 --> 00:51:58.560
They're afraid to-- When their
employer ask them to walk the dog

00:51:58.560 --> 00:52:01.770
which is like the worst thing
you can do for a Caribbean woman

00:52:01.770 --> 00:52:04.400
to ask them to walk a dog.

00:52:04.400 --> 00:52:08.270
And so when they're asked to do
that separate job that's different

00:52:08.270 --> 00:52:10.490
than being a nanny, but they're
not going to say no to it

00:52:10.490 --> 00:52:12.580 position:56%
because they're afraid to get fired.

00:52:12.580 --> 00:52:15.890
They don't know where
their next job might be.

00:52:15.890 --> 00:52:17.770
Many times this status,

00:52:17.770 --> 00:52:20.800
their immigration status
has been used against them.

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:24.910
And they've been-- that people
might threaten them that, you know,

00:52:24.910 --> 00:52:27.440
if you don't do this and if
you don't work, you know,

00:52:27.440 --> 00:52:29.980
seven days a week then
I'll report you.

00:52:29.980 --> 00:52:31.760
Even now they do-- So
they do have rights.

00:52:31.760 --> 00:52:33.240
That doesn't really mean anything.

00:52:33.240 --> 00:52:34.540
They shouldn't be afraid.

00:52:34.540 --> 00:52:36.430
