01:40:17.410 --> 01:40:20.070
Lady on Wheels.

01:40:20.070 --> 01:40:24.350
In a draft of an undated manuscript
entitled "Lady on Wheels" written

01:40:24.350 --> 01:40:29.840 position:56%
by Sidney Robertson Cowell probably
in the 1950s, she drafted a proposal

01:40:29.840 --> 01:40:32.580
for a series of programs,
as she put it,

01:40:32.580 --> 01:40:35.710
about the life of a lady on wheels.

01:40:35.710 --> 01:40:39.190
She explained, "Most of you
know that my chief preoccupation

01:40:39.190 --> 01:40:43.920
for a long time has been the
quote 'Music that's gifted to us',

01:40:43.920 --> 01:40:48.130
as an old lady in North Carolina
once defined folk music to me."

01:40:48.130 --> 01:40:51.420
Robertson traveled
thousands of miles in her car,

01:40:51.420 --> 01:40:55.610
accompanied by her dog, collecting
traditional music and song

01:40:55.610 --> 01:40:59.210
from the 1930s into the 1950s.

01:40:59.210 --> 01:41:05.850
In the "Lady on Wheels" proposal
she wrote, "Folksong is song alive.

01:41:05.850 --> 01:41:10.750
It seems to me that folk song has
gone on living only where new ways

01:41:10.750 --> 01:41:14.990
and new uses for it could give
it freshness and vitality."

01:41:14.990 --> 01:41:19.200
Throughout her ethnomusicological
research, Robertson had no use

01:41:19.200 --> 01:41:22.410
for song as remnant or survival.

01:41:22.410 --> 01:41:25.030
It was living song
that she was after.

01:41:25.030 --> 01:41:27.930
And luckily for us here at
the Library of Congress,

01:41:27.930 --> 01:41:31.190
she left her perceptive
and colorful descriptions

01:41:31.190 --> 01:41:35.000
of the music she recorded and
the performers who sang for her

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:38.020
in ample field notes,
correspondences--

01:41:38.020 --> 01:41:41.630
correspondence and reminiscences
both in the music division

01:41:41.630 --> 01:41:44.610
at the library here and the
American Folklife Center.

01:41:44.610 --> 01:41:50.810
Robertson was born Sidney William
Hawkins in 1903 in San Francisco.

01:41:50.810 --> 01:41:54.520
Precocious, curious and
gregarious from an early age.

01:41:54.520 --> 01:41:57.870
She graduated in Romance
languages from Stanford,

01:41:57.870 --> 01:42:03.390 position:56%
studied music in Paris, and attended
Jung seminars in Zurich and London.

01:42:03.390 --> 01:42:08.090
By the late 1920s, Robertson was
back in California teaching music

01:42:08.090 --> 01:42:11.820
at the progressive Peninsula
School in Menlo Park,

01:42:11.820 --> 01:42:15.520
and excited to be attending
lectures on world music

01:42:15.520 --> 01:42:17.850
at the San Francisco
Conservatory given

01:42:17.850 --> 01:42:21.590
by composers Ernest
Bloch and Henry Cowell.

01:42:21.590 --> 01:42:25.980
Here I will refer to
her as Robertson,

01:42:25.980 --> 01:42:28.460
the name she acquired
from her first marriage.

01:42:28.460 --> 01:42:32.380
Later, after the California project
and her marriage to Henry Cowell,

01:42:32.380 --> 01:42:34.810
she was called Sidney
Robertson Cowell.

01:42:34.810 --> 01:42:39.130
Here's a picture taken
in 1929 when she was

01:42:39.130 --> 01:42:42.420
in her 30s-- in her 20s, excuse me.

01:42:42.420 --> 01:42:45.580
In 1936, while visiting
friends in Washington,

01:42:45.580 --> 01:42:49.690
Robertson met Charles Seeger,
then in charge of the music unit

01:42:49.690 --> 01:42:51.860
at the Resettlement Administration.

01:42:51.860 --> 01:42:54.830
She soon became his
assistant and also proficient

01:42:54.830 --> 01:42:57.930
at making instantaneous
disc recordings.

01:42:57.930 --> 01:43:01.050
As she put it, "I got
hooked on the work

01:43:01.050 --> 01:43:04.390
and the wonderful hopeful
and dedicated new deal.

01:43:04.390 --> 01:43:08.570
So when Charlie asked me to
stay on, I couldn't resist."

01:43:08.570 --> 01:43:11.920
With Resettlement and then the
Farm Security Administration,

01:43:11.920 --> 01:43:16.620
Robertson traveled thousands of
miles on her own making hundreds

01:43:16.620 --> 01:43:19.540
of recordings of traditional
music throughout the south,

01:43:19.540 --> 01:43:22.100
the Ozarks and into the Midwest.

01:43:22.100 --> 01:43:25.920
When funds from Washington for
further recording dried up,

01:43:25.920 --> 01:43:31.240
she gave her remaining contacts
to Alan Lomax for his later forays

01:43:31.240 --> 01:43:35.860
into Croatian, Finnish, and other
communities in the Upper Midwest

01:43:35.860 --> 01:43:38.250
and she returned to San Francisco.

01:43:38.250 --> 01:43:42.510
There she hoped to create a survey
of northern California folk music

01:43:42.510 --> 01:43:45.470
on her own by recording
English language

01:43:45.470 --> 01:43:48.980
and what she called minority
immigrant groups supported

01:43:48.980 --> 01:43:53.720
through the WPA, the Works
Project Administration.

01:43:53.720 --> 01:43:55.450
Without giving much background here

01:43:55.450 --> 01:43:58.490
on the complicated process
it entailed, let me just say

01:43:58.490 --> 01:44:02.310
that she was successful and
it was quite an achievement.

01:44:02.310 --> 01:44:06.330
Robertson was 33, energetic,
outgoing and eager

01:44:06.330 --> 01:44:11.340
to record what people were singing
wherever and whenever she could.

01:44:11.340 --> 01:44:15.280
She secured co-sponsorship for
the project from the Library

01:44:15.280 --> 01:44:19.050
of Congress, which among other
things sent blank acetate discs

01:44:19.050 --> 01:44:20.960
for making recordings.

01:44:20.960 --> 01:44:23.110
And from the University
of California Berkeley,

01:44:23.110 --> 01:44:26.650
she was provided an
office on Shattuck Avenue

01:44:26.650 --> 01:44:31.170
for 20 workers she handpicked
from the California relief rolls

01:44:31.170 --> 01:44:34.030
and were required by the WPA.

01:44:34.030 --> 01:44:39.030
Once the project opened, Robertson
supervised the staff during the day

01:44:39.030 --> 01:44:43.470
and in the evenings and on the
weekend she took her baby portable

01:44:43.470 --> 01:44:46.900
presto recording machine as she
called it, new on the market

01:44:46.900 --> 01:44:52.390
at that time, out and about to
make recordings wherever she could.

01:44:52.390 --> 01:44:55.880
Here she is making copies
for the Library of Congress

01:44:55.880 --> 01:44:57.180
of the recordings that were made.

01:44:57.180 --> 01:45:03.560
So from October 1938 through early
1940, Robertson recorded 35 hours

01:45:03.560 --> 01:45:07.350
of music from numerous California
performers on the project.

01:45:07.350 --> 01:45:11.740
WPA staff took photos and made
technical drawings of many

01:45:11.740 --> 01:45:13.380
of the musical instruments.

01:45:13.380 --> 01:45:15.810
She hoped that her project
would become a prototype

01:45:15.810 --> 01:45:18.650
for the collection of folk
music across the country,

01:45:18.650 --> 01:45:20.930
something that had
never been done before,

01:45:20.930 --> 01:45:25.710
especially with the inclusion of
the music of recent immigrants.

01:45:25.710 --> 01:45:29.770
It is really hard to describe
the breadth of genres recorded

01:45:29.770 --> 01:45:33.420
from so many cultural
groups in 10 minutes.

01:45:33.420 --> 01:45:37.230
Two thirds of the recording were
what she called minority groups.

01:45:37.230 --> 01:45:42.710
She was sensitive as we are
now about the word foreign.

01:45:42.710 --> 01:45:47.190
She-- So she called the minority
groups Armenians, Basques, Finns,

01:45:47.190 --> 01:45:50.270
and you see this quite
impressive list.

01:45:50.270 --> 01:45:54.260
Then one third of the collection
was English-language material.

01:45:54.260 --> 01:45:58.560
And she even went so far as to call
some of the migrants from Wisconsin

01:45:58.560 --> 01:46:03.650
in the Upper Midwest immigrants to
sort of level the playing ground

01:46:03.650 --> 01:46:05.340
of what she was recording.

01:46:05.340 --> 01:46:07.570
She was very aware of this.

01:46:07.570 --> 01:46:11.730
In the September 1938 San Francisco
Chronicle article, Robertson wrote

01:46:11.730 --> 01:46:14.210
about California's
rich cultural heritage,

01:46:14.210 --> 01:46:17.890
including the Native
Americans, the early Spanish

01:46:17.890 --> 01:46:20.960
and Portuguese arrivals,
and the discovery of gold

01:46:20.960 --> 01:46:25.420
which brought settlers from five
continents and the seven seas.

01:46:25.420 --> 01:46:28.280
How can we believe that
these successive waves

01:46:28.280 --> 01:46:31.600
of hardworking citizens
contributed nothing

01:46:31.600 --> 01:46:34.890
to California beyond
the work of their hands?

01:46:34.890 --> 01:46:36.820
What traditions came with them?

01:46:36.820 --> 01:46:40.290
What were they thinking and
feeling as they labored in mines

01:46:40.290 --> 01:46:45.730
and forests, herding cattle and
sheep along the slopes, plowing

01:46:45.730 --> 01:46:49.070
and harvesting in the valleys
and fishing along our coasts?

01:46:49.070 --> 01:46:52.240
Their songs will tell
us if we can find them.

01:46:52.240 --> 01:46:54.580
How does one find songs, she asked.

01:46:54.580 --> 01:46:56.350
They are everywhere at hand.

01:46:56.350 --> 01:46:59.030
A man changing a tire
on Shattuck Avenue

01:46:59.030 --> 01:47:03.560 position:56%
in Berkeley last month sang an old
ballad as he worked and was startled

01:47:03.560 --> 01:47:07.470
by an urgent request to repeat
it so it could be written down.

01:47:07.470 --> 01:47:10.220
A receipt for a bill for a rail--

01:47:10.220 --> 01:47:13.780
paid to a railway express
deliveryman was signed

01:47:13.780 --> 01:47:15.420
with a Basque name.

01:47:15.420 --> 01:47:18.120
This led to a whole nest of songs.

01:47:18.120 --> 01:47:22.440
And one man in Chester County
offered to outsing the gas tank

01:47:22.440 --> 01:47:24.510
if he might ride along to Fresno.

01:47:24.510 --> 01:47:31.060
My thought is to give you a
teeny taste of the recordings.

01:47:31.060 --> 01:47:35.680
These two recordings, if I
can fit them in, are portions,

01:47:35.680 --> 01:47:40.520
feature songs about
the homeland that many

01:47:40.520 --> 01:47:45.630
of the immigrants left behind
central to the story of migration.

01:47:45.630 --> 01:47:47.530
This is Rouben Baboian.

01:47:47.530 --> 01:47:51.560
Robertson attended all sorts
of events of the Armenians,

01:47:51.560 --> 01:47:56.790
visited their coffee shops and she
was entranced by the lively variety

01:47:56.790 --> 01:47:59.690
of music making she
found in the community.

01:47:59.690 --> 01:48:04.210 position:56%
Her field reports tell that Mr.
Baboian was an unusually fine singer

01:48:04.210 --> 01:48:06.170
who had learned all
his songs as a boy

01:48:06.170 --> 01:48:10.920
in the Armenian mountains near
Van, currently in Eastern Turkey.

01:48:10.920 --> 01:48:13.450
The role of folk singer
was traditionally

01:48:13.450 --> 01:48:15.620
in his father's family, she wrote.

01:48:15.620 --> 01:48:18.610
And he learned these songs
in the pure Armenian style,

01:48:18.610 --> 01:48:21.360
free of any Turkish taint.

01:48:21.360 --> 01:48:26.420
Andouni is an Armenian folk song
often translated as the homeless.

01:48:26.420 --> 01:48:30.900
Following the First World War and
the Armenian genocide in 1915,

01:48:30.900 --> 01:48:32.420
that included massacres

01:48:32.420 --> 01:48:35.940
and deportations near
Baboian's original home.

01:48:35.940 --> 01:48:39.730 position:56%
And this song has become
emblematic of the losses experienced

01:48:39.730 --> 01:48:43.680
by Armenians and continues to
hold great symbolic meaning

01:48:43.680 --> 01:48:45.980
for those in the diaspora.

01:48:47.510 --> 01:49:12.830
[ Singing ]

01:49:12.830 --> 01:49:14.840
Next slide, please.

01:49:14.840 --> 01:49:19.810
Elinor Rodriguez was one of
three women from Puerto Rico

01:49:19.810 --> 01:49:24.810
who sang children songs and games,
Christmas songs or aguinaldos

01:49:24.810 --> 01:49:28.290
and other popular tunes
for Robertson in Oakland

01:49:28.290 --> 01:49:30.070
where many Puerto Ricans migrated.

01:49:30.070 --> 01:49:34.730
And Elinor Rodriguez's
version of "Lamento Borincano",

01:49:34.730 --> 01:49:37.370
a sense of heartfelt
emotion and deep longing

01:49:37.370 --> 01:49:41.160
for Puerto Rico infused her
singing although her pronunciation

01:49:41.160 --> 01:49:43.350
and articulation reflect the fact

01:49:43.350 --> 01:49:46.860
that she was a second
generation Puerto Rican.

01:49:49.510 --> 01:49:54.500
[ Singing ]

01:50:01.040 --> 01:50:03.340
OK.

01:50:06.510 --> 01:50:24.130
[ Singing ]

01:50:24.130 --> 01:50:26.480
This popular bolero
was and continues

01:50:26.480 --> 01:50:30.510
to be a heartfelt song among Puerto
Ricans with his nostalgic imagery

01:50:30.510 --> 01:50:34.040
and sense of longing
for the homeland.

01:50:34.040 --> 01:50:38.660
So this has been a mere
glimpse of the valuable

01:50:38.660 --> 01:50:42.160
and expensive California folk
music project collection organized

01:50:42.160 --> 01:50:45.430
and carried out single handedly
by a remarkable, ambitious

01:50:45.430 --> 01:50:49.030
and open-minded collector
in only 17 months

01:50:49.030 --> 01:50:51.350
