01:56:34.510 --> 01:56:39.610
And I'd like to talk to you a
little bit about Recovering Voices

01:56:39.610 --> 01:56:43.140
and I'll finish with-- in to talk--

01:56:43.140 --> 01:56:48.850
talking about the Breath of Life
Institute which is a big focus

01:56:48.850 --> 01:56:51.070
of our work in Recovering Voices.

01:56:51.070 --> 01:56:57.320
Sorry, I'm having to use
my two hands to navigate.

01:56:57.320 --> 01:57:02.580
It's a little confusing but--
So, the Recovering Voices as we'd

01:57:02.580 --> 01:57:06.220
like to call it a response from
the Smithsonian Institution

01:57:06.220 --> 01:57:09.530
to the language endangerment
and knowledge--

01:57:09.530 --> 01:57:13.810
endangerment of knowledge
systems crisis around the world.

01:57:13.810 --> 01:57:18.220
So, the 6 or 7000 languages
spoken around the world,

01:57:18.220 --> 01:57:23.250
it's known that at least a third,
if not more, are in the process

01:57:23.250 --> 01:57:26.380
of being replaced by the other
more dominant languages whether

01:57:26.380 --> 01:57:28.960
regionally or internationally
and it could--

01:57:28.960 --> 01:57:32.810
The forecast suggest
that as many as 90%

01:57:32.810 --> 01:57:36.430 position:56%
of these languages could potentially
go silent by the end of the century.

01:57:36.430 --> 01:57:37.940
So, what can the museum do?

01:57:37.940 --> 01:57:43.570
We have articulated an approach
based on research, on languages

01:57:43.570 --> 01:57:46.460
and knowledge systems to understand
the loss of cultural diversity

01:57:46.460 --> 01:57:48.980
and develop effective
responses to reverse it.

01:57:48.980 --> 01:57:52.320
This is based on access
to collections.

01:57:52.320 --> 01:57:55.590
So, this access is central to
the recovery and generation

01:57:55.590 --> 01:57:57.740
of knowledge in the process.

01:57:57.740 --> 01:58:00.080
And global impact is
achieved through partnerships

01:58:00.080 --> 01:58:02.490
with communities and
academic institutions,

01:58:02.490 --> 01:58:06.760
one of them being the
Library of Congress.

01:58:06.760 --> 01:58:12.960
What distinctive competence
do we offer?

01:58:12.960 --> 01:58:15.760
Among many assets at the museum,

01:58:15.760 --> 01:58:18.530
we have the National
Anthropological Archives.

01:58:18.530 --> 01:58:23.210
And also within the many assets
at the NAA are 9000 linear feet

01:58:23.210 --> 01:58:29.180
of manuscript dating back to the--
the bulk dates back to the 1800s

01:58:29.180 --> 01:58:32.420
but we have manuscripts
that go back to the 1600s

01:58:32.420 --> 01:58:34.820
from everywhere around the world.

01:58:34.820 --> 01:58:40.190
In addition, we have a very
extensive collection of film

01:58:40.190 --> 01:58:47.620
at the Human Studies Film Archives,
as well as photographs and artwork.

01:58:47.620 --> 01:58:51.130
In-- Outside the archives
in our collections,

01:58:51.130 --> 01:58:58.250
we have over 126 million objects,
and that means natural specimens.

01:58:58.250 --> 01:59:01.440
It means mineral samples.

01:59:01.440 --> 01:59:06.320
It means ethnographic
material culture collections.

01:59:06.320 --> 01:59:09.750
So, the point is to
capitalize on these collections

01:59:09.750 --> 01:59:14.390
and on the intellectual capital
of the institution to be able

01:59:14.390 --> 01:59:16.210
to put these strengths
to the services

01:59:16.210 --> 01:59:19.140
of community based
researchers who are looking

01:59:19.140 --> 01:59:24.250 position:56%
to revitalize their languages,
their knowledge systems or cultures.

01:59:24.250 --> 01:59:27.770 position:56%
We have two programmatic and we
have several programmatic activities

01:59:27.770 --> 01:59:29.170 position:56%
but two of them that I want to focus

01:59:29.170 --> 01:59:32.420
on today are the Community Research
Program and the National Breath

01:59:32.420 --> 01:59:35.950
of Life Archival Institute
for Indigenous Languages.

01:59:35.950 --> 01:59:39.320
I'll just say National
Breath of Life for short.

01:59:39.320 --> 01:59:44.100
Community Research
Program, this is a program

01:59:44.100 --> 01:59:48.650
through which we fund
a visit to our museum

01:59:48.650 --> 01:59:51.630
or our institution collections,
not exclusively the museum,

01:59:51.630 --> 01:59:54.270 position:56%
for community research who have us--

01:59:54.270 --> 01:59:58.850
of an articulated project
for revitalization

01:59:58.850 --> 02:00:01.280
of language, of knowledge
or culture.

02:00:01.280 --> 02:00:08.670
And so we will fund up to $10,000
in travel expenses for a group,

02:00:08.670 --> 02:00:12.660
preferably intergenerational,
preferably interdisciplinary,

02:00:12.660 --> 02:00:17.870
but not tied to any specific
academic credentials to come

02:00:17.870 --> 02:00:21.400
and carry out research
in collections, again,

02:00:21.400 --> 02:00:26.840
at the National Museum of Natural
History or NMAI or any other unit

02:00:26.840 --> 02:00:29.630
in the Smithsonian
although it tends to--

02:00:29.630 --> 02:00:32.690
the research tends to
focus on the collections

02:00:32.690 --> 02:00:35.130
of the these two museums.

02:00:35.130 --> 02:00:40.480
And National Breath of Life,
the National Breath of Life,

02:00:40.480 --> 02:00:44.530
it follows the model of the
California Breath of Life

02:00:44.530 --> 02:00:50.200
which began in the 1990s and
takes place every two years.

02:00:50.200 --> 02:00:54.710
And it's some-- it's a training
program to provide capacity.

02:00:54.710 --> 02:00:57.390
It's a capacity build of--

02:00:57.390 --> 02:01:04.700
program to train researchers from
communities on research on archives

02:01:04.700 --> 02:01:08.930
and research in linguistics for the
purposes of language reclamation.

02:01:08.930 --> 02:01:12.750
At the origin in California,
the focus was on tribes

02:01:12.750 --> 02:01:15.960
who no longer had first
language speakers.

02:01:15.960 --> 02:01:21.150
This later expanded and
two institutes were held

02:01:21.150 --> 02:01:23.420 position:56%
in Oklahoma at the Sam Noble Museum.

02:01:23.420 --> 02:01:27.820
We have held three National
Breath of Life Institutes

02:01:27.820 --> 02:01:30.230
and we now have funding secured

02:01:30.230 --> 02:01:33.310 position:56%
from the National Science Foundation
Documenting Endangered Languages

02:01:33.310 --> 02:01:41.860
program to hold the 2017 institute
May 29 to June 9th of next year.

02:01:41.860 --> 02:01:46.530
So, the point is to
bring researchers to DC

02:01:46.530 --> 02:01:49.030
so that they can have access
to the unparalleled collections

02:01:49.030 --> 02:01:51.290
at the National Museum
of Natural History,

02:01:51.290 --> 02:01:54.080
notably the Anthropological
Archives, the National Museum

02:01:54.080 --> 02:01:59.210
of the American-Indian and
the Library of Congress.

02:01:59.210 --> 02:02:03.180
The objective is to familiarize
participants with the holdings

02:02:03.180 --> 02:02:06.970
at these institutions, teach
fundamentals of linguistics

02:02:06.970 --> 02:02:10.200
so that they can begin to read
and interpret the materials.

02:02:10.200 --> 02:02:13.110
So, for this purpose each
participant gets paired

02:02:13.110 --> 02:02:17.370
up with an academically
trained linguist.

02:02:17.370 --> 02:02:21.570 position:56%
And from day one they work on the
analysis of manuscripts on languages

02:02:21.570 --> 02:02:23.500
that they're interested in.

02:02:23.500 --> 02:02:28.390
They discuss and demonstrate ways
that materials can be utilized

02:02:28.390 --> 02:02:31.500
for purposes of language
revitalization and learning

02:02:31.500 --> 02:02:34.530
and provide optional short
sessions on computer technology,

02:02:34.530 --> 02:02:37.990 position:56%
dictionary development, song
writing, writing systems, et cetera.

02:02:37.990 --> 02:02:44.120
We are-- We have now worked
with over 50 languages

02:02:44.120 --> 02:02:48.240
and we'll add another
14 or 15 in 2017.

02:02:48.240 --> 02:02:53.130
It has been critical to
partner with the Library

02:02:53.130 --> 02:02:57.720
of Congress especially
given our joint history tied

02:02:57.720 --> 02:03:00.950
to the Federal Cylinder Project.

02:03:00.950 --> 02:03:04.210
So, the materials here,
the songs are--

02:03:04.210 --> 02:03:09.340
the prayers are really
critical to these researchers.

02:03:09.340 --> 02:03:12.980
These researchers get very
technical linguistics training

02:03:12.980 --> 02:03:15.850
so that they can decide
for so to speak some

02:03:15.850 --> 02:03:20.080
of the language documentation
produce by linguists.

02:03:20.080 --> 02:03:23.850
But they're really, really
more interested in being able

02:03:23.850 --> 02:03:27.690
to regain cultural knowledge
that is in these collections.

02:03:27.690 --> 02:03:31.500
And in that respect, the Library of
Congress collection is essential.

02:03:31.500 --> 02:03:32.800
Thank you.

02:03:32.800 --> 02:03:34.600
&gt;&gt; Todd Harvey: Thank you.

