02:08:55.340 --> 02:08:57.640
&gt;&gt; Kelly Navies: Good afternoon.

02:08:57.640 --> 02:08:58.960
My name is Kelly Navies.

02:08:58.960 --> 02:09:00.900
I'm the museum specialist
oral historian

02:09:00.900 --> 02:09:02.570
at the Smithsonian National Museum

02:09:02.570 --> 02:09:04.830
of African-American
History and Culture.

02:09:04.830 --> 02:09:08.370 position:56%
I would like to thank the Library of
Congress for inviting me here today.

02:09:08.370 --> 02:09:11.180
We are as you know very busy.

02:09:11.180 --> 02:09:12.770
But I'm very happy
to be on this panel,

02:09:12.770 --> 02:09:16.380
and I'm glad that you're here, Mr.
Bishop, because I never met you.

02:09:16.380 --> 02:09:18.010
This is my first time meeting you.

02:09:18.010 --> 02:09:20.590
I'm relatively new so I
actually wasn't there for all

02:09:20.590 --> 02:09:22.830
of the interviews that he's
talking about but I'm going

02:09:22.830 --> 02:09:25.440
to share a little bit
more about that project.

02:09:25.440 --> 02:09:29.310
The oral history program at
the Smithsonian National Museum

02:09:29.310 --> 02:09:31.320
of African-American
History and Culture is

02:09:31.320 --> 02:09:33.830
as you know a new and
evolving program.

02:09:33.830 --> 02:09:37.710
Our goal is to produce and
collect oral history content

02:09:37.710 --> 02:09:39.260
for our growing collection.

02:09:39.260 --> 02:09:42.240
In addition, we are committed to
making this material accessible

02:09:42.240 --> 02:09:45.440
and usable to our many
publics, general, scholars,

02:09:45.440 --> 02:09:47.930
researchers, teachers and students.

02:09:47.930 --> 02:09:50.040
These various constituency
should be able

02:09:50.040 --> 02:09:52.590
to access oral history
materials not just recordings

02:09:52.590 --> 02:09:55.430
but associated documentation
both online

02:09:55.430 --> 02:09:57.730
and by coming into the museum.

02:09:57.730 --> 02:10:00.850
In addition, our collection is
intended to support the work

02:10:00.850 --> 02:10:04.430
and research of our curators
as they develop exhibitions.

02:10:04.430 --> 02:10:07.510
In the years prior to our
opening and prior to my joining

02:10:07.510 --> 02:10:09.870
with the program, we began
to collect oral histories

02:10:09.870 --> 02:10:12.040
through our collaboration
with the Library of Congress

02:10:12.040 --> 02:10:13.670
on the civil rights
oral history project.

02:10:13.670 --> 02:10:16.650
And you've been hearing
a little bit about that.

02:10:16.650 --> 02:10:20.400
The civil rights history
project began in 2009

02:10:20.400 --> 02:10:24.350
when the US Congress passed the
Civil Rights History Project Act.

02:10:24.350 --> 02:10:27.350
This law directed the Library of
Congress and the National Museum

02:10:27.350 --> 02:10:28.810
of African-American
History and Culture

02:10:28.810 --> 02:10:32.860
to conduct a nationwide survey of
existing oral history collections

02:10:32.860 --> 02:10:36.020
with relevance to the civil
rights history movement,

02:10:36.020 --> 02:10:37.750
and to record new interviews
with people

02:10:37.750 --> 02:10:39.720
who participated in the movement.

02:10:39.720 --> 02:10:43.360
There have been approximately
144 interviews conducted

02:10:43.360 --> 02:10:45.110
and recorded on film.

02:10:45.110 --> 02:10:48.000
Some of these interviews are
with well know movement icons,

02:10:48.000 --> 02:10:50.820
but many others are with
less known individuals

02:10:50.820 --> 02:10:53.160
who played important
roles in the movement.

02:10:53.160 --> 02:10:55.860
The significance of these
interviews is immense.

02:10:55.860 --> 02:10:58.930
Their content reveals the work
and day-to-day experiences

02:10:58.930 --> 02:11:00.910
of major players not
just in the south

02:11:00.910 --> 02:11:02.440
but throughout the United States.

02:11:02.440 --> 02:11:05.810
For example, the most recent
cohort of interviews were done

02:11:05.810 --> 02:11:07.880
in Southern California
with former members

02:11:07.880 --> 02:11:11.330
of the Black Panther Party
and the Brown Berets.

02:11:11.330 --> 02:11:15.110
One of my favorite interviews
is with Freeman Hrabowski.

02:11:15.110 --> 02:11:18.500
Dr. Hrabowski is known mostly
in academic circles for his work

02:11:18.500 --> 02:11:21.800
as the president of the University
of Maryland, Baltimore County

02:11:21.800 --> 02:11:24.860
where he has developed a highly
successful math and science program

02:11:24.860 --> 02:11:26.160
that targets those

02:11:26.160 --> 02:11:28.380
who are historically
represented in those fields.

02:11:28.380 --> 02:11:31.150
What is less known is his
role in the Children's Crusade

02:11:31.150 --> 02:11:35.030
of Birmingham, Alabama and the
fact that he was actually friends

02:11:35.030 --> 02:11:36.960
with the four girls who
were killed in the bombing

02:11:36.960 --> 02:11:40.740
at the 16th Street
Baptist Church in 1963.

02:11:40.740 --> 02:11:43.580
During his interview
with Dr. Joe Mosnier

02:11:43.580 --> 02:11:46.290
of the Southern Oral History
Program at UNC Chapel Hill

02:11:46.290 --> 02:11:48.290
where I'm also from, by the way.

02:11:48.290 --> 02:11:51.750
Dr. Hrabowski gives a poignant
and moving telling of this chapter

02:11:51.750 --> 02:11:54.230
in his life and the
life of our nation.

02:11:54.230 --> 02:11:56.960
In story, one is struck by
the trajectory of his life

02:11:56.960 --> 02:11:59.530
from the upheaval and
trauma of those early years

02:11:59.530 --> 02:12:02.120
to his contemporary role
as a committed activist

02:12:02.120 --> 02:12:04.360
in the sphere of academics.

02:12:04.360 --> 02:12:06.750
What this and other
oral history interviews

02:12:06.750 --> 02:12:09.780
from this collection reveal
is that beyond the retelling

02:12:09.780 --> 02:12:13.120
of historical events, oral
histories have the power to inspire

02:12:13.120 --> 02:12:16.660
and trigger the much
needed healing process.

02:12:16.660 --> 02:12:20.180
As a nation we are still grappling
with the trauma of racial violence

02:12:20.180 --> 02:12:22.590
and it is one of the goals
of the National Museum

02:12:22.590 --> 02:12:25.520
of African-American History and
Culture to be a place of healing

02:12:25.520 --> 02:12:27.660
as well as a place of learning.

02:12:27.660 --> 02:12:29.980
With the availability
of this collection,

02:12:29.980 --> 02:12:33.990
a visitor can view the display of
Emmett Till's coffin, and then go

02:12:33.990 --> 02:12:37.120
and listen to the reflections
of those like the Ladner sisters

02:12:37.120 --> 02:12:41.890
who were directly impacted
by Till's murder in 1955.

02:12:41.890 --> 02:12:44.870 position:56%
Another strength of the civil rights
history project is the diversity

02:12:44.870 --> 02:12:46.170
it portrays.

02:12:46.170 --> 02:12:48.190
In addition to the
integration of the well known

02:12:48.190 --> 02:12:51.600
with the less celebrated, it also
showcases stories of non-black

02:12:51.600 --> 02:12:54.240
such as Luis Zapata, a
Latino-American who grew

02:12:54.240 --> 02:12:57.560
up in Orange County,
California and became active

02:12:57.560 --> 02:12:59.230
in the United Farm Workers.

02:12:59.230 --> 02:13:02.430
And then moved to Mississippi
to become active in both SNCC

02:13:02.430 --> 02:13:05.270
and the Mississippi
Freedom Labor Union.

02:13:05.270 --> 02:13:07.630
Then there's the story of
David and Satoko Ackerman,

02:13:07.630 --> 02:13:10.520
an interracial couple,
Caucasian and Japanese,

02:13:10.520 --> 02:13:13.640
who met at the Chicago Theological
Seminary and were then recruited

02:13:13.640 --> 02:13:16.210
by fellow student Jesse
Jackson to join the march

02:13:16.210 --> 02:13:18.640
from Selma to Montgomery.

02:13:18.640 --> 02:13:21.160
There are also many interviews
with the women of the movement

02:13:21.160 --> 02:13:23.900
like Dr. Kathleen Cleaver
of the Black Panther Party,

02:13:23.900 --> 02:13:27.920
and sisters Joyce and Dorie Ladner
who have led lifetimes of activism

02:13:27.920 --> 02:13:30.170
through involvement
in the NAACP, SNCC,

02:13:30.170 --> 02:13:33.330
and in many other campaigns
for justice.

02:13:33.330 --> 02:13:35.390
The cultural and gender
diversity displayed

02:13:35.390 --> 02:13:38.730
in these interviewees provides
a more complete picture

02:13:38.730 --> 02:13:42.300
of what we call the movement
and it reaches our understanding

02:13:42.300 --> 02:13:45.480
of the contextual experience
of those we call activist.

02:13:45.480 --> 02:13:46.990
What motivates them?

02:13:46.990 --> 02:13:49.990
What are their lives like
on a day-to-day basis?

02:13:49.990 --> 02:13:51.740
There are also interviews
with siblings

02:13:51.740 --> 02:13:53.820
and whole families would
shed light on the ways

02:13:53.820 --> 02:13:57.330
in which the civil rights movement
impacted not just individuals

02:13:57.330 --> 02:14:00.590
but social networks
and entire communities.

02:14:00.590 --> 02:14:03.820
I've already used this collection
to introduce foreign students

02:14:03.820 --> 02:14:05.760
to our oral history collection.

02:14:05.760 --> 02:14:08.010
Students from Southeast
Asia were very interested

02:14:08.010 --> 02:14:11.470
in how oral history enables one
to capture stories of trauma

02:14:11.470 --> 02:14:13.230
and oppression and
were anxious to go home

02:14:13.230 --> 02:14:16.940
and record their own stories, as
well as interview their relatives.

02:14:16.940 --> 02:14:21.140
One of the reasons I am so
passionate about oral history is

02:14:21.140 --> 02:14:23.060
that there are so many
layers of meaning

02:14:23.060 --> 02:14:26.040
and so many ways of
using the material.

02:14:26.040 --> 02:14:29.210
I look forward to presenting
oral history to our many publics

02:14:29.210 --> 02:14:31.040
through exhibits and
variety of programs

02:14:31.040 --> 02:14:33.010
and through training and workshops.

02:14:33.010 --> 02:14:35.840
The civil rights history project
is a good model for the kind

02:14:35.840 --> 02:14:39.140
of oral history work we
plan to do, collaborations

02:14:39.140 --> 02:14:41.810
with other institutions that
produce rich oral histories

02:14:41.810 --> 02:14:45.710
that have multifaceted
meanings and applications.

02:14:45.710 --> 02:14:48.630
Most recently, I have been
directing an oral history project

02:14:48.630 --> 02:14:51.040
with individuals who
donated significant items

02:14:51.040 --> 02:14:53.290
and artifacts to our collection.

02:14:53.290 --> 02:14:56.260
As a museum, our oral history
collection is deeply connected

02:14:56.260 --> 02:14:58.460
to the material collection.

02:14:58.460 --> 02:15:00.040
There are interviews
with artifact donors

02:15:00.040 --> 02:15:02.800
that reveal not just the
provenance of particular pieces

02:15:02.800 --> 02:15:06.240
but also the relationship of
these items to the lives of those

02:15:06.240 --> 02:15:08.770
who once possessed them
and how these stories fit

02:15:08.770 --> 02:15:10.070
into the larger narrative

02:15:10.070 --> 02:15:12.150
of African-American
history and culture.

02:15:12.150 --> 02:15:13.600
Yeah, I'll take questions later.

02:15:13.600 --> 02:15:16.510
OK. Thank you.

02:15:16.510 --> 02:15:20.500
[ Applause ]

