&gt;&gt; Lance Ledbetter: Hi, I'm Lance
Ledbetter from Dust-to-Digital.

02:15:30.950 --> 02:15:34.060
As Todd was saying, we
are a record company.

02:15:34.060 --> 02:15:38.860 position:56%
My-- It's just my wife and myself
and we're based in Atlanta, Georgia.

02:15:38.860 --> 02:15:42.450
I think a record company like ours,

02:15:42.450 --> 02:15:46.210
there's not really a
roadmap for what we do.

02:15:46.210 --> 02:15:50.780
We've sort of evolved over time
but I want to walk through today

02:15:50.780 --> 02:15:54.150
and kind of tell the story
about how we got to work

02:15:54.150 --> 02:15:57.340
with such great archive as
the Library of Congress,

02:15:57.340 --> 02:16:02.540
the Florida Folklife Program,
the Center for Southern Folklife,

02:16:02.540 --> 02:16:05.650
the Association for Cultural
Equity and the University

02:16:05.650 --> 02:16:08.220
of Georgia Archives among others.

02:16:08.220 --> 02:16:11.840
Our label started in
2003 with the release

02:16:11.840 --> 02:16:14.640
of a box set called
"Goodbye, Babylon".

02:16:14.640 --> 02:16:18.700
And what we were trying to do
with that set was, you know,

02:16:18.700 --> 02:16:22.220
it's all gospel music
recorded between 1902 to 1960.

02:16:22.220 --> 02:16:26.410
But what we're trying to do is
provide access point to this sort

02:16:26.410 --> 02:16:30.900
of overwhelming amount of
content by showing like subgenres

02:16:30.900 --> 02:16:33.490
of the different styles
of gospel music.

02:16:33.490 --> 02:16:36.640
We worked with musicologists like
Dick Spottswood, Charles Wolfe

02:16:36.640 --> 02:16:41.140
and Tony Russell to produce a
set that sort of told the story

02:16:41.140 --> 02:16:44.540
of gospel music while making
various objective selections

02:16:44.540 --> 02:16:45.940
to get people an access point.

02:16:45.940 --> 02:16:51.230
During the four and a half years to
produce "Goodbye, Babylon" we sort

02:16:51.230 --> 02:16:55.480
of set the standards, aesthetic
standards and mission of our label.

02:16:55.480 --> 02:17:00.870
We decided we want to produce
high quality cultural artifacts.

02:17:00.870 --> 02:17:05.450
And what I mean by that is we want
to have topnotch documentation

02:17:05.450 --> 02:17:09.160
with beautiful packaging
and terrific design.

02:17:09.160 --> 02:17:13.070
We thought that the music was so
important we want to elevate it to,

02:17:13.070 --> 02:17:15.080
you know, to this thing
that was beautiful

02:17:15.080 --> 02:17:16.770
where people will hopefully
pay attention.

02:17:16.770 --> 02:17:18.880
And that was back in '03

02:17:18.880 --> 02:17:23.880
when there's a lot less
distractions than there are now.

02:17:23.880 --> 02:17:28.360
In 2004, Art Rosenbaum and I met.

02:17:28.360 --> 02:17:30.340
And Art Rosenbaum,
for those of the--

02:17:30.340 --> 02:17:34.910 position:56%
for those of you that don't know, he
made field recordings for probably

02:17:34.910 --> 02:17:39.110
about 40 years in their house at
the University of Georgia Archives

02:17:39.110 --> 02:17:41.260
where Art was a professor.

02:17:41.260 --> 02:17:45.030 position:56%
Art and I had several conversations.

02:17:45.030 --> 02:17:47.700
He was a fan of "Goodbye,
Babylon" and we talked

02:17:47.700 --> 02:17:52.320
about possibly doing something
similar, like a similar model

02:17:52.320 --> 02:17:54.710
for his field recordings.

02:17:54.710 --> 02:17:59.650
So Art and I spent about a year
and a half just listening to all

02:17:59.650 --> 02:18:03.460
of his recordings and it was just--
it was a great, great experience

02:18:03.460 --> 02:18:08.300
to do that with somebody as
incredible as Art Rosenbaum.

02:18:08.300 --> 02:18:10.540
And the set we produced
was called "Art

02:18:10.540 --> 02:18:13.310
of Field Recording"
that came out in 2008.

02:18:13.310 --> 02:18:18.880
It was well received and it was
our first work with an archive.

02:18:18.880 --> 02:18:21.390
It was with the University
of Georgia Archive.

02:18:21.390 --> 02:18:23.260
Before that time, we
were only working

02:18:23.260 --> 02:18:25.920
with private record collectors.

02:18:25.920 --> 02:18:29.250
Like I said, the set
was well received,

02:18:29.250 --> 02:18:31.600
actually, even won a Grammy Award.

02:18:31.600 --> 02:18:36.730
And we were so excited but at
the same time my wife and I,

02:18:36.730 --> 02:18:40.280
although it was a terrific
experience, we realized, you know,

02:18:40.280 --> 02:18:44.080
to take a year and a half to listen
to audio and still be a, you know,

02:18:44.080 --> 02:18:47.730
functioning recording company
and putting out records,

02:18:47.730 --> 02:18:51.370
we needed to refine that
process a little bit.

02:18:51.370 --> 02:18:52.670
So we did.

02:18:52.670 --> 02:18:55.280
You know, we started to
hear from other archives.

02:18:55.280 --> 02:18:58.400
You know, I think the "Art of
Field Recording" set sort of put us

02:18:58.400 --> 02:19:04.170
on the archival map with people
that had lots of great material.

02:19:04.170 --> 02:19:07.580
The next set that we did with
an archive was the "Drop on Down

02:19:07.580 --> 02:19:08.880
in Florida" set which was a--

02:19:08.880 --> 02:19:12.240
it was a reissue of a double LP

02:19:12.240 --> 02:19:18.870
that the Florida State Folklife
Program have put out in the 1980s

02:19:18.870 --> 02:19:20.760
and they want to do like
an expanded edition.

02:19:20.760 --> 02:19:24.310
So we kept their original notes.

02:19:24.310 --> 02:19:27.920
We expand the liner notes and we
expand the audio to be two CDs.

02:19:27.920 --> 02:19:33.220
It's almost like double the audio
material as the original double LP.

02:19:33.220 --> 02:19:36.960
But in doing so, we worked
a lot with the archive.

02:19:36.960 --> 02:19:39.370
We let them develop a lot of the--

02:19:39.370 --> 02:19:42.350
make a lot of the decisions
in the development stages.

02:19:42.350 --> 02:19:47.580
What we sort of shifted our
expertise to was more in the--

02:19:47.580 --> 02:19:51.280
helping them with the concepts,
the packaging and the design,

02:19:51.280 --> 02:19:54.880
the marketing, the
manufacturing and the distribution.

02:19:54.880 --> 02:19:57.750
And that set was well received too.

02:19:57.750 --> 02:20:01.420
We didn't win a Grammy but
it was very well received.

02:20:01.420 --> 02:20:05.380
And it came together very well
and it sort of tested this sort

02:20:05.380 --> 02:20:09.680
of new approach for us to where
we can work with an archive

02:20:09.680 --> 02:20:12.790
and have them using their
expertise in their field

02:20:12.790 --> 02:20:15.420
and us using our expertise
in our field.

02:20:15.420 --> 02:20:18.690
So since then we've worked

02:20:18.690 --> 02:20:22.320
with several more archives
including the Library of Congress.

02:20:22.320 --> 02:20:27.430
We worked with Jim Leary at the
University of Wisconsin to do a set

02:20:27.430 --> 02:20:29.910
of folk songs from another America.

02:20:29.910 --> 02:20:34.340
And we-- That was a partnership
with the University Press,

02:20:34.340 --> 02:20:36.670
the University of Wisconsin Press.

02:20:36.670 --> 02:20:40.160
And since then we've done another
Library of Congress project.

02:20:40.160 --> 02:20:43.710
We did the-- It was sort of similar
to the "Drop on Down in Florida"

02:20:43.710 --> 02:20:47.770
where it was originally put out as
a three LP set in the '70s "Music

02:20:47.770 --> 02:20:51.060
of Morocco" which was
recorded by Paul Bowles.

02:20:51.060 --> 02:20:55.990
And that set that came out earlier
this year has been probably one

02:20:55.990 --> 02:21:00.030
of our best received
projects and in several years.

02:21:00.030 --> 02:21:02.990
So, you know, I want to just
kind of say how, you know,

02:21:02.990 --> 02:21:07.140
what our process is, how we've
evolved to work with more archives.

02:21:07.140 --> 02:21:10.650
And I think what we, you know,
as a label bring to the--

02:21:10.650 --> 02:21:14.870
to this, you know, the sharing
is with a physical package,

02:21:14.870 --> 02:21:16.600
you have a beginning
and you have an end.

02:21:16.600 --> 02:21:19.780
And you can direct people, you
know, to the infinite archive.

02:21:19.780 --> 02:21:24.150
The online material, you know,
that's something that we can help,

02:21:24.150 --> 02:21:29.880
you know, raise awareness of what
archives have in the context of,

02:21:29.880 --> 02:21:35.270 position:56%
you know, consumerism and record
nerds and, you know, all that stuff.

02:21:35.270 --> 02:21:38.930
